VIBRIO ALGINOLYTICUS, WATER EXPOSURE - NETHERLANDS
***************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: Thu, 9 Nov 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Eurosurveillance weekly release [edited]
<http://www.eurosurveillance.org/ew/2006/061109.asp#3>

During the summer of 2006, wound infections in
bathers caused by _Vibrio_ species were reported
from several European countries. In Germany, 3
people were reported to have developed _Vibrio
vulnificus_ infections (1), and 3 people from
southeast Sweden were infected with
non-agglutinating and non-toxin-producing _V.
cholerae_ (2). The 3 patients from Germany and 2
patients from Sweden had underlying (chronic)
illnesses. All these infections were associated
with contact with water in the Baltic Sea. In
Denmark, the clinical microbiology departments
have diagnosed 15 human infections with seawater
bacteria of the genus Vibrio in 2006, mainly skin
and ear infections with _V. alginolyticus_ and
_V. parahaemolyticus_ (3).
On 24 Jul 2006, 3 people in the Netherlands were
reported to have developed infections due to
_Vibrio alginolyticus_ after swimming in the
Oosterschelde, a large inlet on the North Sea, at
separate but nearby locations. Patient A was a
73-year-old woman who had fallen on her knee,
resulting in an injury; _V. alginolyticus_ was
isolated from the synovial fluid of the knee
joint. Patient B was an 18-year-old woman who had
a wound on one of her hands from which the
bacterium was cultured. Patient C was an
11-year-old boy who developed otitis after
swimming. _V. alginolyticus_ was isolated from
one of his ears. The patients were treated with
amoxicillin-clavulanate and rapidly recovered
after antibiotic treatment. No new cases have
since been reported.
Water samples were taken from the Oosterschelde
on 28 Aug, 4 Sep and on 4, 11 and 18 Oct 2006.
Both _V. alginolyticus_ and _V. parahaemolyticus_
were frequently detected in 0.1-1.0 mL volumes of
these samples.
_V. alginolyticus_ is a halophilic Gram-negative
bacterium that is part of normal marine flora.
The bacterium is able to multiply in salty waters
at elevated water temperatures (4). _V.
alginolyticus_ is one of 12 recognized marine
_Vibrio_ species that have been identified as
being pathogenic for humans (5). It has been
associated with wound infections (6), ear
infections (7), but also with gastroenteritis (8)
and bacteremia in immunocompromised patients
after consumption of raw shellfish (9). _V.
parahaemolyticus_ infections have been associated
with gstroenteritis after consumption of
contaminated seafood (5), and the _V.
parahaemolyticus_ bacterium can also infect open
wounds exposed to warm seawater (10).
High temperatures were recorded throughout Europe
in summer 2006, and the increase in water
temperature was favorable for the growth of
_Vibrio_ species. Climate changes, leading to a
northerly shift of warm summer weather and
elevated water temperatures in the moderate
climate regions of northwestern Europe in future
years are expected to increase exposure of
bathers to indigenous waterborne pathogens for
which growth opportunities increase (11), such as
pathogenic marine _Vibrio_ species.
1. Frank C, Littman M, Alpers K, Hallauer J:
Vibrio vulnificus wound infections after contact
with the Baltic Sea, Germany. Euro Surveill
2006;11(8):E060817.1. Available from:
<http://www.eurosurveillance.org/ew/2006/060817.asp#1>.
2. Andersson Y, Ekdahl K: Wound infections due to
Vibrio cholerae in Sweden after swimming in the
Baltic Sea, summer 2006. Euro Surveill
2006;11(8):E060803.2. Available from:
<http://www.eurosurveillance.org/ew/2006/060803.asp#2>.
3. Andersen PH: Infections with seawater bacteria. EPI-NEWS 2006; ( 26-32):1.
(<http://www.ssi.dk/graphics/en/news/epinews/2006/PDF/2006-26_32-final-www_2.pdf>)
4. Morris JG Jr: Cholera and other types of
vibriosis: a story of human pandemics and oysters
on the half shell. Clin Infect Dis 2003;37:
272-80.
5. Oliver JD, Kaper JB: Vibrio species. In: Doyle
MP, Beuchat LR, Montvilee TJ (Eds) Food
Microbiology ï¿½ Fundamentals and Frontiers. ASM
Press. Washington DC, p. 228-64.
6. Opal SM, Saxon JR: Intracranial infection by
Vibrio alginolyticus following injury in salt
water. J Clin Microbiol 1986; 23: 373-74.
7. Hornstrup MK, Gahrn-Hansen B: Extraintestinal
infections caused by Vibrio parahaemolyticus and
Vibrio alginolyticus in a Danish county,
1987-1993. Scan J Infect Dis 1993;25: 735-40.
8. Caccamese SM, Rastegar DA: Chronic diarrhea
associated with Vibrio alginolyticus in an
immunocompromised patient. Clin Infect Dis
1999;29: 946-47
9. Chien JY, Shih JT, Hsuch PR, et al: Vibrio
alginolyticus as the cause of pleural empyema and
bacteremia in an immunocompromised patient. Eur J
Clin Microbiol Infect Dis 2002;21: 401-403.
10. Daniels NA, MacKinnon L, Bishop R, et al:
Vibrio parahaemolyticus infections in the United
States, 1973-1998. J Infect Dis 2000; 181:
1661-66.
11. Schijven JF, de Roda Husman AM: Effect of
climate changes on waterborne disease in the
Netherlands. Wat Sci Techn 2005;51: 78-87.
